The Presidency says Zuma has pledged his continued support towards assisting the Public Protector&#8217;s office in fulfilling its mandate. JOHANNESBURG - President Jacob Zuma and Public Protector Busisiwe Mkhwebane have had their first meeting since her appointment to office. The meeting was held at the presidential headquarters in Pretoria on Tuesday morning. Mkhwebane took over in October amid an ongoing battle between the Public Protector s office and Zuma over the State of Capture report. The Presidency says Zuma has pledged his and government s continued support towards assisting the Public Protector s office in fulfilling its mandate.Presidency spokesperson Bongani Ngqulunga said: The President reiterated the input of all Chapter Nine institutions in our constitutional democracy. Advocate Mkhwebane in turn thanked President Zuma for the opportunity to meet and said she looked forward to constructing a working relationship with government. (Edited by Winnie Theletsane)